¶ ⦊
  ‖ \ssection{Why} ⦉

  ‖ We can characterize the dependence of two events in terms
    of the rank of a particular matrix. ⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ \ssection{Definition} ⦉

  ‖ Given a probability measure $𝗣: \powerset{Ω} → 𝗥$ on the
    finite set $Ω$ and two events $A, B ⊂ Ω$, the ❬joint
    probability matrix❭ of $A$ and $B$ is the matrix
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ M = \bmat{ ⦉

      ‖ 𝗣(A ∩ B) ❲&❳ 𝗣(A ∩ \relcomplement{B}{Ω}) ᜶ ⦉

      ‖ 𝗣(\relcomplement{A}{Ω} ∩ B) ❲&❳ 𝗣(\relcomplement{A}{Ω} ∩
        \relcomplement{B}{Ω}) ᜶ ⦉

      ‖ }. ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Since $B$ and $\relcomplement{B}{Ω}$ partition $Ω$, use the
    the total law of probability to express is $𝗣(A) = 𝗣(A ∩
    B) + 𝗣(A ∩ \relcomplement{B}{Ω})$. ⦉

  ‖ Likewise, $𝗣(\relcomplement{A}{Ω}) = 𝗣(\relcomplement{A}{Ω} ∩ B)
    + 𝗣(\relcomplement{A}{Ω} ∩ \relcomplement{B}{Ω})$. ⦉

  ‖ For these reasons, the sum of the entries of the first row
    of $M$ is $𝗣(A)$ and the sum of the entries of the second
    row of $M$ is $𝗣(\relcomplement{A}{Ω})$. ⦉

  ‖ The events $A$ and $B$ are independent if and only if
    $\rank(M) = 1$ ⦉
⦉

